@@eThe Scorching Sands: Certification District Review@@N

@@yBureau of Eastern Routes, Standards and Verification Division@@N
@@dFiled under: Audit Systems, Contract Law, Administrative Collapse@@N

The Scorching Sands once operated as a @@yfraud-resistant certification
district@@N -- and our Standards Division recognized it as kindred work.
Sun-fired verification clay that changed color irreversibly when
tampered with. The @@yBurn Ledger@@N -- a semi-buried audit complex
recording kiln batches, water allotments, and passage fees in one
integrated archive. Our @@WOath of the Kept Record@@N committee noted
that the Sands' integrated approach exceeded our own ledger
architecture in elegance, if not durability.

The @@yScorch Clause@@N is contract law we @@erespect@@N. Supplemental water
allocation for cargo in transit, mandatory heat-certification of seal
materials, liability segmented by route rather than total journey.
The Scorch Clause anticipated maritime-style risk segmentation
generations before the Saltglass Reach formalized it. Our Bureau
maintains a translated copy in @@dstandards reference, eastern drawer,
second shelf@@N.

The @@gEmber Wardens@@N operate under @@d"No crossing without measure"@@N --
a principle so close to our @@WOath of the Counted Step@@N that our
assessors have classified them as @@ya parallel administrative
tradition@@N.

What failed was not the system's design but its @@rsupply chain@@N.
When the Iseth dried, the certification district lost the resource
base that made its audits meaningful. Kiln houses without water
allotments became empty ritual spaces. The Burn Ledger recorded
transactions for goods that no longer moved through routes that no
longer functioned. The forms persisted. The substance evaporated.

The @@rAshbound Reavers@@N are logistics predators exploiting the gap
between surviving procedure and collapsed supply. The @@dCauterist
Synod@@N that brands false seals as heresy has transformed quality
control into theology -- a corruption our own Violet Compact-era
clerks would recognize with discomfort.

Three daily heat phases -- @@rHard Glare@@N, @@yBreathfire@@N, @@dFalse
Mercy@@N -- govern survival in ways our patrol manuals have formally
incorporated for eastern convoy advisories. We cannot govern the
Sands. But we can @@yread their records@@N, and what we read is a
system that died of thirst while its paperwork remained perfect.

The Continuity faction cites the Sands as proof that good systems
require stable resources. The Reckoning faction cites the Sands as
proof that @@rperfect records do not prevent institutional death@@N.
